ction(\"Braised Cod with White Wine\")` → the regex matches `^braised\\b` → but wait, `looksLikeCookingInstruction` has a word count check: `if (words.length < 4) return false`. \"Braised Cod with White Wine\" has 5 words, which is >= 4. So it DOES match as a cooking instruction!\n\n**That's the bug!** The text `Braised Cod with White Wine` is being rejected as a cooking instruction because `braised` is in `COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` and it has >= 4 words.\n\nThe same issue applies to `Roasted Beet and Walnut Dip` — `roasted` is in the instruction starts regex. After repair: `Roasted Beet and Walnut Dip` (5 words >= 4) → rejected as cooking instruction.\n\nAnd for `Drożdże Sernik` — after repair the title line becomes `Drożdże Sernik` which is only 2 words, so cooking instruction doesn't fire. But the body line `Podawać letni lub chłodny.` — wait, the iter 30 changes added `podawa[cć]` to the Polish instruction starts and the `4→a` OCR normalization. So `Podaw4ć letni lub chłodny.` should become `Podawać letni lub chłodny.` (4 words) → caught by Polish cooking instruction starts. But the result says it still extracted \"Podawać letni lub chłodny.\" — oh wait, the mid-sentence-boundary check in `isLikelyGarbled` should catch the period: `Podawać letni lub chłodny.` ends with a period, but there's no `. ` followed by a letter, so that check doesn't fire.\n\nActually wait — let me re-read the result for Drożdże Sernik: `Podawać letni lub chłodny.` — this is the output after OCR normalization. But the hard filter should catch it:\n1. `looksLikeCookingInstruction(text)` where text = `Podaw4ć letni lub chłodny.` — Polish regex needs to match `podaw4ć` which starts the line, but `podawa[cć]` won't match `podaw4ć`. \n2. Then the OCR normalization step: `ocrNormForInstruction` replaces `4→a` adjacent to letters: `(?<=[a-zà-ż])4` → `Podaw` then `4` with preceding `w` (lowercase) → `a`, yielding `Podawać letni lub chłodny.`. Then `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Podawać letni l