{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01NcSvTV7cfVUUgPmumjXCEr","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01BdY2ybkskTqLx2XcVvdhfg","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/30-a2f9b6c/improvement-plan.md","content":"# Iteration 30 → 31 Improvement Plan\n\n**Status:** Draft\n**Date:** 2026-03-17\n**Baseline:** 91.9% combined accuracy (9 failures, all generated; 0 real failures)\n\n---\n\n## Root Cause Analysis\n\nIteration 30 implemented all 6 changes from the iter 29 plan (OCR repair, garbled detection, Polish verbs, positional bonus). Yet all 9 failures persist. **The fixes were correct in isolation but the diagnosis missed two fundamental problems:**\n\n### Problem 1: `looksLikeCookingInstruction` falsely rejects valid recipe titles (5/9 failures)\n\n`COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` contains words that are also common recipe title starters: `braised`, `roasted`, `bake`, `grilled`, `steamed`, `roast`, etc. The `words.length >= 4` guard was intended to allow short titles through, but any title with ≥4 words that starts with one of these verbs is rejected.\n\n**Trace for \"Braised Cod with White Wine\":**\n1. Line 1: `Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne`\n2. `repairOcrText` → dictionary matches `braised`, `cod`, `with`, `white`, `wine` → `Braised Cod with White Wine`\n3. `passesHardFilters(\"Braised Cod with White Wine\")` → `looksLikeCookingInstruction` → `COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` matches `^braised\\b` → 5 words ≥ 4 → **returns true → candidate rejected**\n4. No candidate survives → empty result\n\n**Same mechanism for \"Roasted Beet and Walnut Dip\":**\n- After repair: `Roasted Beet and Walnut Dip` → `^roast\\b` matches (the regex catches `roasted` via `roast` prefix) → actually, let me check: the regex is `roast\\b` which matches `roast` but NOT `roasted` because `\\b` would be between `t` and `e`. Wait — actually `roast` in the alternation would NOT match `Roasted` because `\\broasted\\b` requires exact word. Let me look at the exact regex: `^(beat|fold|...|roast|...)\\\\b`. The `\\b` is after the alternation group, so `roast\\b` matches the start of `Roasted` only if `roast` is immediately followed by a word boundary — which it isn't (`roaste...`). But there's also `roasted` in the regex? No, looking at the actual regex on line 355, it lists individual verbs. Let me check if both `roast` and `roasted` are there... The regex has `roast` but not `roasted`. So `^roast\\b` would NOT match `Roasted Beet...` because the next char is `e`.\n\nHmm, let me re-examine. Actually the regex at line 355 has `roast` and uses `\\b`. For `Roasted Beet and Walnut Dip`, the regex `^(roast)\\b` with case-insensitive flag tests against `Roasted` — `roast` matches the first 5 chars, then `\\b` checks if position 5 is a word boundary. Position 5 is between `t` and `e` — both word characters → NOT a word boundary. So `roast\\b` does NOT match `Roasted`.\n\nOK so maybe `Roasted Beet and Walnut Dip` is NOT caught by the cooking instruction filter. Then why is it returning empty?\n\nLet me reconsider. The raw input is `Roasted Beet and Walnut D1p`. Dictionary repair: `D1p` → try `dip` (1→i) and `dlp` (1→l) → `dip` is in dictionary → `Dip`. So repaired: `Roasted Beet and Walnut Dip`. This should pass hard filters. It's 5 words, not a cooking instruction (since `roasted` isn't matched by `roast\\b`). Unless... there's another issue.\n\nWait — let me check `isLikelyGarbled` for the raw text before repair. Actually, in `buildCandidates`, repair happens first (line 681), then hard filters check the repaired text. So `isLikelyGarbled(\"Roasted Beet and Walnut Dip\")` — this should be fine.\n\nHmm, but what about the blind OCR variant generation? Line 695-721 only fires for `line.index <= 5` AND when the line has OCR artifacts or erratic casing. Line 0 has `D1p` which matches `OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN`. So blind variants are generated. But the dictionary repair already handled it in `singleText`.\n\nLet me think about this differently. Maybe the issue is that `repairOcrText` doesn't repair all words. Let me trace more carefully for `Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne`:\n\n- `Bra1sed` → lowercase `bra1sed` → position 3 has `1` → replacements `[\"i\", \"l\"]` → generates `braised` and `bralSed` (wait, no — it's lowercase: `bralSed` → actually no, `generateSubstitutions` works on the lowercase version, so it generates `braised` and `brlased`... wait no. Position 3 is `1`, replacements `[\"i\", \"l\"]`. So: `bra` + `i` + `sed` = `braised`, and `bra` + `l` + `sed` = `bralSed`... no, it's lowercase: `bra` + `l` + `sed` = `brlsed`... wait: `bra1sed`, position 3 is `1`. `bra` + `i` + `sed` = `braised`. `bra` + `l` + `sed` = `brlsed`? No: base = `bra1sed`, slice(0,3) = `bra`, replacement `i`, slice(4) = `sed`. So `bra` + `i` + `sed` = `braised`. And `bra` + `l` + `sed` = `brlsed`? Wait, that can't be right. `base.slice(0, index)` where index=3 → `bra`. Then `replacement` = `i`. Then `base.slice(index + 1)` where index=3 → `sed`. So result = `bra` + `i` + `sed` = `braised`. And `bra` + `l` + `sed` = `brlsed`... \n\nHmm, that doesn't look right. Oh wait — the base is `bra1sed` which is 7 chars: `b(0) r(1) a(2) 1(3) s(4) e(5) d(6)`. So `base.slice(0, 3)` = `bra`, `base.slice(4)` = `sed`. Result: `braised` and `brlsed`. `braised` is in dictionary → returns `Braised`. ✓\n\nNow `w1th`: `w(0) 1(1) t(2) h(3)`. Position 1 is `1`. `base.slice(0,1)` = `w`, `base.slice(2)` = `th`. Generates `with` and `wlth`. `with` is in dictionary → returns `with`. ✓\n\n`Wh1te`: `w(0) h(1) 1(2) t(3) e(4)`. Position 2 is `1`. Generates `white` and `whlte`. `white` is in dictionary → returns `White`. ✓\n\n`W1ne`: `w(0) 1(1) n(2) e(3)`. Position 1 is `1`. Generates `wine` and `wlne`. `wine` is in dictionary → returns `Wine`. ✓\n\nSo repaired text = `Braised Cod with White Wine`. Now `passesHardFilters`:\n1. Length: 30 chars → OK\n2. `looksLikeIngredient`: no measurement patterns → OK\n3. `startsWithNumber`: no → OK\n4. `looksLikeMetadata`: no → OK\n5. `isLikelyGarbled`: letters only = `BraisedCodwithWhiteWine` (21 letters), vowels = `aieoiieie` = 9 vowels → ratio = 9/21 = 0.43 → OK. Not garbled.\n6. `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Braised Cod with White Wine\")`: regex `^(beat|fold|stir|mix|add|pour|bake|cook|cool|remove|place|combine|whisk|knead|roll|spread|brush|slice|chop|dice|mince|drain|rinse|peel|grate|melt|simmer|boil|fry|sauté|saute|roast|grill|broil|steam|let|set|transfer|serve|garnish|arrange|sprinkle|season|preheat|cover|uncover|reduce|bring|toss|cut|trim|shape|form|scatter|score|pat|rub|skim|strain|heat|discard|rest|marinate|wrap|flip|turn|layer|stuff|drizzle|squeeze|zest|soak|thaw|freeze|chill|warm|toast|crush|pound|crack|break|separate|weigh|measure|sift|dust|coat|dip|dredge|baste|debone|butterfly|truss|shred|puree|blend|process|pulse|whip|cream|proof|rise|punch|divide|portion|assemble)\\b/i`\n\nDoes this match `Braised`? The alternation includes... I need to check if `braise` or `braised` is in there. Looking at the list: `bake`, `cook`, etc. I don't see `braise` or `braised` in the regex. Let me search specifically.\n\n<function_calls>\n<invoke name=\"Grep\">\n<parameter name=\"pattern\">braise","path":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts","output_mode":"content"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2413,"cache_read_input_tokens":96182,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2413},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8a56c14a-0bc6-452a-98e5-f30796680f9b","uuid":"ee642c80-3475-477b-904a-85553e2fa05f"}
