{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01CF7PKob2xCZXkk8xVLbH2J","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Interesting! Any parenthetical line on line 2 causes the failure. The issue is NOT specific to `(OCR ...`. Let me check what `passesHardFilters` does with the parenthetical line and, more importantly, what `corroboration` does with the title candidate.\n\nWait — actually, let me check `isLikelyGarbled` on the parenthetical. `(OCR CORRUPTION: digit for letter, hyphenation)` — this starts with `(`, not a lowercase letter. After filtering through `passesHardFilters`:\n\n1. `(OCR CORRUPTION...)` → length 48, OK\n2. Not ingredient\n3. Not starting with number\n4. Not metadata\n5. `isLikelyGarbled`: starts with `(` which is not `[a-z]`, so the lowercase check doesn't fire. But wait, the parenthetical check `if (/^\\(OCR\\b/i.test(text.trim())) return false` should catch `(OCR CORRUPTION...)`. So this line IS filtered.\n\nBut `(Something else entirely)` or `(digit for letter, hyphenation)` — these don't match `^\\(OCR\\b`. And they also don't match `^\\(.*\\bcorruption\\b`. The second one has \"corruption\" in it? No — `(digit for letter, hyphenation)` doesn't contain \"corruption\". \n\nLet me check: `(Something else entirely)` — does it pass hard filters?\n\nActually, there's a simpler check I'm missing: `if (/^\\(.*\\bcorruption\\b/i.test(text.trim())) return false;`. For `(digit for letter, hyphenation)` → no \"corruption\" → not filtered. \n\nBut wait, even `(Something else entirely)` causes the failure. So it's not about filtering the annotation line — it's about something else.\n\nLet me think... The parenthetical is at position 2. `buildCandidates` creates the candidate from line 0 as `Braised Cod with White Wine`. Then line 2 `(Something else entirely)` also enters processing. After `stripParentheticalGloss` and `passesHardFilters`, does it become a candidate?\n\nActually, `(Something else entirely)` — `stripPageNumber` does nothing, `stripTrailingPageRef` does nothing, `stripParentheticalGloss` matches but... let me check: the function expects the form `base (paren)`. For `(Something else entirely)` the entire thing is in parentheses, so the regex `^(.+?)\\s*\\(([^)]+)\\)\\s*$` tries to match. `.+?` needs at least one char before `\\(`. There's nothing before the opening paren. So it doesn't match. The text stays as `(Something else entirely)`.\n\nThen `repairOcrText(\"(Something else entirely)\")` — no OCR artifacts, stays same.\n\nThen `passesHardFilters(\"(Something else entirely)\")`:\n- Length 26, OK\n- Not ingredient, not number, not metadata\n- `isLikelyGarbled`: starts with `(`, which is lowercase? No, `(` is not a letter. `text.replace(/[^a-zA-Z]/g, \"\")` = `Somethingelseen tirely` = `Somethingelseentirely` — vowel ratio check should be fine. Then the \"starts with lowercase\" check: `text.trim()` = `(Something else entirely)`, `text.trim()` doesn't start with `[a-z]`. But... one word check: `(Something` — hmm, this might get caught by the garbled word check. `words = [\"(Something\", \"else\", \"entirely)\"]`. Check each for garbled: `else` starts with lowercase, `e` length 4, not in commonShort2 → BUT pure-lowercase length is checked: `else`.replace(/[^a-z]/g, \"\") = `else` → length 4. The check is `<= 2`. 4 > 2, so not garbled.\n\nOK, the parenthetical line should actually pass or fail hard filters based on specific checks. But more importantly, even if it becomes a candidate, why would it cause the TITLE candidate to be removed?\n\nOh wait — I bet the issue is the `corroboration` check! The title `Braised Cod with White Wine` needs its content words to be corroborated elsewhere in the document. With \"Some other text here\" in the document, there might be words that overlap. But with only `(OCR CORRUPTION...)` and `lngredients:`, the words `Braised`, `White`, `Wine` don't appear elsewhere.\n\nLet me check the corroboration logic: it's used in the multi-title guard and in the pre-threshold corroboration filter. For 0 ALL_CAPS candidates or 1, the corroboration filter shouldn't apply. Let me re-read:\n\nLine 1401-1414: `allCapsInScored` — filters for `isAllCaps(s.text)`. `Braised Cod with White Wine` is NOT all caps. So `allCapsInScored.length` would be 0. No corroboration filter applies.\n\nBut then the multi-title guard at line 1600+: `selected.length > 1` — if there's only one candidate, this doesn't fire.\n\nHmm, let me just check if `(Something else entirely)` actually passes hard filters."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":874,"cache_read_input_tokens":113577,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":874},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8a56c14a-0bc6-452a-98e5-f30796680f9b","uuid":"32775b25-421e-4d11-b1f8-8b70421cd91a"}
